The midpoint $M$ of $\overline{AC}$ is
\[\left( \frac{3 + 7}{2}, \frac{4 + 10}{2} \right) = (5,7).\]Then $\overrightarrow{AB} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{7 - 3}{2} \\ \frac{10 - 4}{2} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix},$ so the vector perpendicular to $\overline{AB}$ is $\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}.$

Thus, letting $B = (3,4) + \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} = (5,7),$ we can take
\[(p,q) = (-3,2).\]Then the line perpendicular to $\overline{AB}$ through $B$ is
\[\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} x - 5 \\ y - 7 \end{pmatrix} = 0,\]which simplifies to $-3x + 2y = -1.$ Solving for $y$ gives
\[y = \frac{3}{2} x + \frac{1}{2}.\]Since $A$ and $C$ lie on this line,
\[4 = \frac{3}{2} \cdot 3 + \frac{1}{2} = \frac{3}{2} \cdot 7 + \frac{1}{2}.\]Thus, $(p,q,s) = \boxed{(-3,2,41)}.$

